<div data-controller="diminishedtriad">
    <h1>Diminished Harmony Player</h1>
    <p>
    A diminished triad is a three-note chord that consists of a root note, a minor third interval above the root, and a diminished fifth interval above the root. In simpler terms, if you start with a note (lets say C), you would add the note three semitones above it (E♭) and then add the note six semitones above the original note (G♭). Put them together, and you have a C diminished triad (C-E♭-G♭).
    </p>
    <p>
    The defining characteristic of a diminished triad is the diminished fifth, which means the fifth is lowered by one semitone compared to a perfect fifth. This creates a tense and dissonant quality in the chord. Diminished triads are often used for their instability and the desire to resolve to more stable chords.

    In summary, a diminished triad consists of a root note, a minor third, and a diminished fifth, giving it a dissonant and unstable sound.
    </p>
